<p>Rhodes Scholarship (Lost to Sanchit Bansal)</p>

<p>I did not understand their psychology: if I had been in their position, what would I look for in a candidate? I would look for academic excellence - which I have - but which I underplayed. Â I thought by underplaying my academics, I exhibited authenticity. But I was projecting. Instead of authenticity, I exhibited weakness and fear. When you are looking for a job, you have to present yourself as if the job is made for you, and you for the job, and you have to know it yourself, understand the criteria, and be that. Â The interviewerâ€™s job was to pick the best candidates; their anxiety is picking the false cases: Â so you have to do your best to make their job easier.Â </p>

<p>When solving the game theory problem, I under-communicated. I did not explain and break down my thinking into smaller steps. (Instead I said something like â€œbackward inductionâ€). I mistakenly thought the the other person, being a prominent game theorist, wasÂ on the same plane as me and comprehended fully what I was saying. But again, this was projecting:Â Â  I myself would not have understood what I was saying had I met myself after a few months - just like Rohan Paul did not when I replayed the interview with him.Â </p>

<p>I played games andÂ lost out on authenticity and trust. For example, at the end of the interview, I asked â€œMay i know your name?â€. I thought this gesture would impinge on the minds of the interviewers and make me stand our of the crowd. But again, I was projecting. To the interviewers, this would have seemed odd, awkward, and out of sorts at best, disrespectful at worse.Â </p>

